segments.text: The 101st Airborne, 173rd Light Infantry had a battalion there.
All these were organized into a group called Task Force South.

One of the outfits that was there was Charlie Company 75th Rangers, and they formed what were called long-range reconnaissance patrols, six-man teams that would go out into the jungle, in the valley, in the mountain areas.
and look for the enemy.
And by this time, about six months into my tour, the North Vietnamese were starting to come into the province, and they'd go out and try and find them, and then call in support to kill them.
And so my job was to help put them into the jungle.
I'd fly up and guide the helicopters into various landing zones, LZs,
We'd know in advance where we were going to let them out.
But then we'd have them go into a couple before and a couple after so the enemy wouldn't know where we let them out, hopefully.
I flew in support of them while they were out there.
If they got scared or had radio contact, I flew at night in support of them.
We always had an alert pilot at night.
And some of my more interesting things happened at night.
And then we'd help pick them up.
We had some pretty exciting times picking them up as well.
So I had a very mission load, and it made it really, really interesting.
And to use the word fun sounds inappropriate, but it really was.
It was exciting, and I felt that I did a valuable job.
I felt that I did it very well.
And my main mission was bailing Americans out of trouble.
I will tell you this is one key thing.
When you had a contact, which is what we called countering the enemy, you had more people wanting to get on the action than you could handle.
When you had an American in trouble, you had an unbelievable number of people wanting to help out.
Americans looked out for each other.
Good.
Do you feel that there was any, this is kind of like wading into that again,
Do you feel that there was any racial discrimination and or racial tension, if so?
Not where I was.
I know it existed other places, but not where I was.
There was none where I was.
That just didn't matter?
It just didn't happen.
The guys who were in the rear areas had time on their hands, and they're normally the ones who did most of the drugs and...
had the racial problems that happened in some of the infantry units too, but usually guys that have to depend on each other, depended on each other and became very good friends.
Was there any kind of initiation process?
You talked about that there are some veterans.
Did you feel odd at times because you were the new kid?
Not really.
The one guy who tried to act like he was the veteran and the big combat hero was really sort of a jerk.
and I figured him out pretty fast, so most of the veterans were very helpful.
Did you dislike the local people other than the enemy that you came in contact with?
How did they feel about you in the United States?
We had Vietnamese observers, and one of our missions was to fly with the Vietnamese in the back seat.
And these guys were pretty good guys.
A couple of them were local.
He lived in Phan Thiet.
A couple of them were what we called Chu Hoys.
They're North Vietnamese who surrendered, or Chu Hoid.
Chu Hoi means I surrender.
And they flew in the back.
We got along real well with them.
Over the course of the year, I lost a great deal of respect for the Vietnamese as a whole because they'd been fighting for a lot of years, and they were tired.
But the communists have been fighting for a lot of years too.
And a lot of the South Vietnamese were giving up, were corrupt, weren't giving their best effort, would not... Americans would fly them into an LZ and have to push them out of the helicopters.
I had a South Vietnamese unit fire at me one time.
I had a South Vietnamese Air Force bird dog pilot fire rockets at American troops.
and he knew they were American troops.
And I actually had, he did that a couple of times and one day we got orders to, if we could shoot him down to do so.
And he flew off and turned his aircraft over to the enemy somewhere.
He left the area.
Did you feel that they wanted y'all there, but they wanted you to do all the work?
Yeah, some wanted us there and wanted us to do all the work.
Others wanted our money.
You know, what they could make off the GIs selling things.
I didn't really care about that.
I had my job to do.
I didn't really care what the Vietnamese thought.
Do you think that other people did?
That they were angry that they weren't fighting as hard as them?
Oh yeah.
Well, I got angry at them too.
I really did.
A lot of Americans were disgusted with the Vietnamese and their
You know, there's a lot of warlike people in the world.
South Vietnamese aren't one of them.
North Vietnamese are.
Americans are fairly warlike.
That's our history.
We're not the only ones, but we're one of them.
I just don't think the South Vietnamese are.
Some were very, very good, but the majority of them were just below average.
Can you describe...
a pleasant memory that you have or an experience that you take?
Well, in country, we had some good parties.
We could get lobster tail for 50 cents.
We were so out by ourselves during that platoon that we had to
We'd go to ration breakdown, and we'd give them rides on our airplanes and invite them to our parties, and so they'd give us steaks.
We went to Fan Rang, which is a big Air Force base halfway between Pantheon and Cameron.
A big Air Force base, just like stateside.
Theaters with plush seats and a real nice officer's club and 10,000-foot runway.
We got two cases of steaks from ration breakdown up there, and
And I flew those two cases and an Air Force guy back to a party that was waiting for me at the LZ in our hangar.
And I got back and the winds were 25 knots and 90 degrees to the runway.
And the plane was overloaded and out of balance because I had one case of stakes in the back behind the guy sitting in the back seat and one on his lap.
And those are heavy things.
Plus we were loaded up with radios and armored seat and all this other stuff.
And it was a foolish, foolish thing to do, but all those guys were waiting for me on the ground for the party to start so they could cook the steaks.
And I had to land, and I thought that was pretty fun.
I did it.
I got it in safely.
You saved the party.
Mm-hmm.
And also, I bailed out some people that were in trouble, but I'll always treasure that.
Mm-hmm.
And the friendships that were.
Mm-hmm.
Oh, we made some good friends and lost some good friends.
Mm-hmm.
Do you think that would be the most difficult part, is losing your friends?
Yeah.
What do you think, losing your friends?
Was being a pilot, do you feel that that was better or worse than other types of?
Far better, far better.
Were you treated better?
Yeah, we were part of the elite and we didn't get our hands too dirty except when we were pre-flight in the airplane.
After I lived six months at the LZ, I moved into the hotel downtown.
which was across the street from a school where Ho Chi Minh taught when he was younger.
And so it was sort of a communist shrine.
As a result, we were never hit while I was there because they were afraid of damage to the school across the street.
Yeah, I lived well.
I had a maid come in every day when I was at the hotel and wash my uniform and polish my boots and make my bed and clean the room and all this kind of stuff.
It was not bad at all.
Was there some resentment from the other types of soldiers?
Not really.
They liked having me overhead when they were in trouble.
And in fact, I could go a number of places and not have to buy a drink because those guys were so glad to see me.
Because they were so dependent on you.
Yeah.
How much contact did you have then with the United States?
You said your wife was over there.
Well, she wasn't there.
I mean, she was in the States.
But another group of people we invited to our parties ran the military radio, the Mars system.
And they could call through, like, call ham operators back in the States.
And they had a little device that they could dial your phone number.
And it was like talking on the radio.
And sometimes I'd

the communication would be bad and so the guy on the other end would have to translate her and I'd tell her I love you over and she'd say I love you over but I could call her I usually call her about every other week I wrote therefore a few letters I wrote a number of letters but not as many as you might think I'm a poor letter writer but I got to call her quite a bit in fact a friend of mine and I were going to go to Hong Kong on
on leave, and the last minute I said to him, I said, you know, you're a nice guy and all, but I'd rather see Ann in Hawaii than you in Hong Kong.
So I called her on the phone and told her to fly to Los Angeles.
She was staying with her parents in Fort Stockton, Texas.
I said, fly to Los Angeles, and if I get out to Hawaii, I'll call you from Guam.
And I called her from Guam, and she got to Hawaii a half hour after I did.
So we went to Hawaii twice, R&R and leave.
That was lucky.
Yeah.
And did she bring your son?
No, but she brought movies.
And I was going to ask you, what kind of information did she pass on to you through, I'm talking media and about how the war was, how people thought of it?
We got Stars and Stripes newspaper, and they were very intellectually honest.
We got the good news and the bad news.
We knew all about the demonstrations and how bad they were getting.
And the news came heavier and heavier.
I was there when Neil Armstrong walked on the moon for the first time, and we got that in Stars and Stripes.
We didn't have television where I was, but we did have radio.
Armed Forces, it's AFVN, Armed Forces Radio Vietnam.
And so we were pretty well informed.
Did that make...
Y'all angry that there were protests going on while you were there?
Yeah, very much so.
What was the worst or most difficult thing about being a pilot?
Well, after I got over being scared, nothing.
I mean, I enjoyed it.
Like I said, I don't want to sound tacky, but I was really pretty good at doing what I did.
And I got to the point, there's a difference between courage and conviction.
Courage is going into a situation that you think you might get hurt and doing it anyway.
Conviction is where you don't think they can touch you because you're that much better.
Well, there were a couple of times where I went into situations where I thought I might get hurt and did it anyway.
But most of the time, I felt they couldn't touch me.
that I could get them before they could get me.
And that's pretty much the way it was.
Do you feel like you had conviction first and then it turned into courage?
I don't know.
The courage just happened when it happened.
You didn't expect it or plan for it.
I think...

There was one time where a team was getting picked up, and they were taking fire, and they were in an exposed position, and they were taking fire from a tree line, and they were at 5,000 feet, which is the top of this one mountain.
And as heavy as my aircraft was, at that altitude, I couldn't climb.
So I had four rockets, and I made four level passes at this tree line, and flew pretty close to it, firing into it.
And then after I was out of rockets, I made two more passes
because I thought maybe they wouldn't know that I was out of rockets.
And it just seemed like the thing to do at the time.
I'll tell you, I was a little antsy, you know, flying at that tree line that close, giving them a level shot at me.
But the other times I would fly at night, and I'd have artillery on call, and I'd turn on all my lights on the aircraft and make it a target, and then I'd see their flashes when they'd fire at me,
And then I'd call the artillery on the flashes.
Well, that was not courage.
That was conviction because I knew that I believed they couldn't hit me, that they were bad shots, and that I could hit them with artillery before they could hit me with ground fire.
So, yeah, there was a couple of courage things, but mostly it was conviction.
You feel that you're very lucky, extremely lucky.
I am lucky to be here a number of times over.
I've had...
One time my son asked me to catalog all the things that happened to me to include after Vietnam and other flying.
I was a flight instructor for a while and I flew for the reserves for a while.
I've had over 30 incidents, 16 of which were life-threatening.
I had several crashes and a flare shoot on my wing and a night in the mountains with no instruments and no radio aids and in and out of clouds.
The flare shoot I could give you if you had time, I could give you a chapter and verse of what happened that night, everything.
I remember every detail.
The night in the mountains, we were looking for a lost IRP team.
I can't tell you how I got in.
I can tell you what happened once I was in, but I can't tell you how I got out.
I just don't know.
It's a blank.
Can you talk about your group of friends, and do you still talk to them?
I've pretty much lost track of them, but I'm going to have a 25-year celebration May 6th of 1995.
I had a 20-year celebration, and that's the day I got back May 6th of 1970.
And so in 1990 I had one, and in 1995 I'm going to have one, and this time I'm going to try and track some of them down.
I kept in touch with a few of them for a while, about four of them.
But, no, actually, one, two, three, four, five, kept in touch with six of them.
And over the years, I'm such a poor letter writer.
I mean, I don't even keep in touch with my relatives.
So I've lost track, but you get to this age, and you want to make those contacts again.
So I'm going to track them down and invite them to the party and figure if I give them a year's notice, they ought to be able to make it.
But I made some really, really good friends, and we did some super things together.
One was an Air Force pilot.
A couple were guys in my platoon.
One guy named Ed Pennington, and as I recall and understand that I'm telling you things best as I remember, he had played football for the University of Texas.
He was a big guy, red-headed guy.
one of the kind of people that everybody gravitates toward.
He was the center of whatever social group was there.
Usually the big men on campus like that, you might think he'd be a little stuck up, but he made everybody feel like they were his close personal friend.
He did not discriminate.
He was nice to everybody.
And a month before he was due to leave,
He took a sweep with a, he was an advisor to a South Vietnamese unit, and he took a sweep for a fellow who was sick, one of the other Americans who was sick.
And he took a direct hit with a mortar round and was killed.
And there were several tragedies that occurred while I was there, but I will tell you that the loss of that individual is as big a loss as I can think of.
So Ed Pennington is somebody I'll always remember.
Do you, I mean, can you kind of remember when you first got home and when you were coming home, the attitudes of yourself, your family, friends, and also other Americans that did not fight?
Well, the first thing that happened was we were, there were a few of us who were getting short.
That's what you call it when you're due to leave.
You go to your date of return from overseas.
It's called DEROS.
And there were

Four or five of us sitting around talking one day, we were all due to leave at about the same time, and we were saying, boy, it's going to be good to get back, and I'm looking forward to getting out of here and go back to the world, and all those expressions that we used.
And I don't remember who it was, but somebody said, you know, I'm going to miss it.
And we all admitted what we had been feeling, but nobody had said was that we were going to miss it.
And if I didn't have a wife and child waiting for me, I would have extended.
Really?
And stayed over there.
because it was an intense experience, one I'll not trade for.
It was really incredible.
But when we were out processing, there were guys who were getting 30-day drops.
They were getting out of country 30 days early.
And helicopter pilots, a lot of the units, would walk up to a guy when he's preparing for a flight one day and say, you're not going, you're not flying anymore.
Anyway, I was supposed to be back in the States on May 5th, and things were a little intense right then, and they were short people.
And on May 3rd, I think it was May 3rd, an American was killed in my province.
You know, we didn't have that many Americans killed.
one to a mine, one to a sniper, one to a mortar round, or a route to a small action or something like that.
But we didn't lose that many.
And so when one was killed, it was a big deal.
And we went after whoever.
And so on May 3rd or 4th, we'd been having a lot of things going on, and I had delayed going to out-process.
And it was May 4th.
was this guy got killed, and so Bobby Beale, the guy who was my stick buddy in flight school and has served with me the whole time there in Fanfiette, which is a real unusual coincidence.
You know, most commissions officers only flew for six months, then would get a ground assignment of some kind.
And I flew the whole year with Bobby.
And we were going to out-process together.
And...
It was just a real strange confluence that put us in the same platoon.
But we did this deal where after a while you could tell if a trail had been used recently because of the color of the dirt on it.
And if you got real low and dropped all your flaps and flew very slow into the wind,
sometimes you could see clearly enough which direction they were going.
You could tell by the footprints.
And so we would fly on the bushes.
And again, that didn't bother me.
I was in control, so it wasn't courage, it was conviction.
But the other guy would fly up high as sort of a cover in case anything popped.
So we were looking for this guy, for this group of guys that killed the American, and didn't find him.
But that was, like,
the day before I was supposed to have gone back.
And I had already called Ann and told her I was on my way.
Well, the protests had been pretty hot and heavy anyway.
And the day after I left, our LZ was hit pretty hard with sappers and the rocket attack.
And somewhere in there was a Cambodian invasion.
So I went to Quignon to out process and went to Nha Trang
for lunch on the way back down and then went to Cameron and gave him, turned over the airplane and went out to the out processing center.
So I actually left the day after I was supposed to.
Well, by that time Kent State had happened.
And they said, if you're in uniform, you're liable to get some pretty rough treatment.
said we could travel out of uniform because they said, you know, people are getting spit on and attacked and stuff like that.
And nobody in my group took their uniform off.
We all traveled in uniform.
We had our TWs and we got our ribbons, you know, and I had the wings.
And I was pretty proud of what I'd done.
So we flew into Seattle Tacoma Airport.
And there were about three of us.
that went into the restaurant there at Sea Tank.
And we couldn't get served.
We'd try and stop a waitress, and they'd just look at us and walk on.
So I made the connection to Midland.
And at Midland Airport, Midland Air Terminal, my wife and her parents were there with my son.
And there was one of those billboards out by the ramp with the stick-on letters.
By that time, I'd made Captain, and it said, Welcome Home, Captain Anderson.
And the first thing I did when I saw that sign was look to see who was going to tear it down.
But I was back in Texas, and things were okay there.
So that's
We went out to California to see my parents, and I was in civilian clothes and went into a shopping mall.
Some hippie said, sign this petition to stop the baby killing in Vietnam.
I have plenty of clearance to shoot people that I thought were civilians, and we didn't shoot.
And Ann just sort of led me away.
But homecoming was not good.
It was good to see Ann and the family, but it was not what my dad received.
Mm-hmm.
No, he deserved everything.
Anyway, what else?
Do you feel that drugs were a problem?
Do you feel that?
Well, they weren't where I was.
They were at the large depots, and I heard that later they were in the line units, but mostly the rear echelon people.
We had some marijuana growing in the wire at Donk 10 where the, not just
my company, but other units were headquartered.
And very so often they'd go burn it out and pretty soon be grown again.
The guys with little to do got bored and a lot of those folks that did drugs there did drugs in the States.
I mean, it wasn't the war that caused them to do drugs.
I'm a student of history now.
Since my generation,
has no idea what your generation went through with Vietnam.
Do you feel that there are some misconceptions that my generation has?
Some half-truths?
Well, yeah, I think so.
The one half-truth is that it's a little falsehood that's been perpetrated that we could not have won.
We did have it won, and we could have won had we fought it like a real war.
That's number one.
We never fought it like a real war.
Johnson had route packages.
He picked targets that were of no significance from the White House, contrary to the advice of his Joint Chiefs of Staff.
He had our pilots who flew into the north, which is some of the toughest flying in history,
That took courage.
That was courageous flying.
They had to follow route packages.
So the North Vietnamese with Russian help put up the most sophisticated air defense the world has ever known along those route packages, and those guys had to fly through that.
That was criminal.
If we'd fought this like a real war, we could have won that war, and no one can tell me otherwise.
Another half-truth is that we made a practice of killing civilians, women and children.
Ann Landers had a column recently in the newspaper where she talked about, she used the expression, trained to kill women and babies.
Ann Landers used that less than a month ago in the paper.
We weren't trained to kill civilians.
We went out of our way to kill, to not kill civilians.
World War II, they made war on the civilian population as a matter of policy.
In Vietnam, we sweated and strained not to kill civilians.
There would be people in a prohibited area, in a free-fire zone that you could shoot anything that moved.
I had clearance to fire and said, no, these are civilians.
We're letting them go.
And that was a judgment call.
They may not have been, but they looked like civilians, and I'd rather not shoot them.
We did a good job.
The people, the American servicemen that I worked with over there were good troops.
They were good at their jobs.
They did it with dedication.
They could have kept their head down for a year and gone home.
But they hung it out to do the job right.
They were good at it.
And like I said earlier, if an American was in trouble, people would do anything to get that American out of trouble.
They would risk their lives on a regular basis
We had a case where a team of these LURPS were going into an LZ.
I was flying high, directing the helicopter from LZ to LZ.
The one we had picked, we set them down.
You always had to know which one you were going to set them on because you need to know where they are.
And they need to know where they get off so they can find their way around.
It was a hillside.
The helicopter set down with one skid on the side of the hill, making sure the rotor blades were
The guys got out of the helicopter.
He took off.
It happened to be what is called a hot LZ, or North Vietnamese in the tree line.
They opened fire on this team and the helicopter.
The helicopter took hits, took one round through the rotor blade, which set up a vibration.
Instead of leaving the area, this guy did as tight a turn as you can do in a helicopter, came back in under fire, sat down on the ground,
and sat there until everybody got on board while he was taking fire and then flew off.
Now you can't get better than that.
His name was Cartwright, by the way.
He was a warrant officer.
Flew for the 192nd.
He was a real big guy and he had a handlebar mustache and so we called him Hoss.
The company commander of that unit
flew out one time to get a guy who'd been hit, who was in triple canopy jungle.

The company commander went out, flew a Huey helicopter down through that triple canopy, hovering, 300 feet off the ground, the tops of the trees, hovered down, moved over, hovered down, moved over, hovered down, until he got down.
He didn't have a penetrator, a jungle penetrator, so he had to get down there to get the guy on board.
He put him on board and he went back up.
Some of the best flying you can imagine.

And the other thing I'd like to say is those same people are now some of your most productive citizens, some of the pillars of the community, some of the best professionals and business people in our society today.
They are not the malcontents that you see that go to every parade looking for sympathy, dressed in this ragtag uniform, saying, oh, woe is me.
Most of those guys either never served in the military or never served in Vietnam
or never served in a combat unit, my perception is the vast majority of them are worthless misfits because the guys that I know who did the
